# Path B · Production Hosting on Ultradian (iteralabs.xyz/atelier)

Concrete runbook for deploying the alive demo to `https://www.iteralabs.xyz/atelier/` (dashboard) and `https://www.iteralabs.xyz/atelier/docs/` (MkDocs) using the **Ultradian** Ubuntu server as the host. Backend stack runs alongside on the same machine; Cloudflare Tunnel terminates TLS and forwards inbound traffic — no port-forwarding, no Let's Encrypt, no public IP required on Ultradian.

```mermaid
flowchart LR
    Internet[Internet user]
    CF[Cloudflare edge<br/>iteralabs.xyz]
    Tunnel[cloudflared<br/>outbound tunnel]
    Webapp[Webapp container<br/>:8080]
    Backend[Backend stack<br/>compose:8000+50051]
    Internet -->|HTTPS| CF
    CF -->|TLS-terminated| Tunnel
    Tunnel -->|localhost:8080| Webapp
    Webapp -->|host.docker.internal:8000| Backend
```

## B.0 · Ultradian inventory (verify these before starting)

Assumptions baked into this runbook — confirm or adjust before running the commands below:

| Item | Assumption | How to verify |
|---|---|---|
| OS | Ubuntu 22.04 LTS or 24.04 LTS | `lsb_release -a` |
| Shell access | ssh from your laptop with sudo on Ultradian | `ssh ultradian.local` (or its LAN IP / hostname) |
| Source tree | `~/git/iteralabs/{atelier-backend,atelier-sdk,atelier-proto,atelier-webapp,atelier-infra}` cloned on Ultradian | `ls ~/git/iteralabs` |
| Docker | not yet installed (idempotent install in B.2) | `docker --version 2>/dev/null \|\| echo MISSING` |
| `cloudflared` | not yet installed (B.5 installs) | `cloudflared --version 2>/dev/null \|\| echo MISSING` |
| Cloudflare zone | `iteralabs.xyz` already imported into your Cloudflare account | check Cloudflare dashboard → Websites |
| Ports on the LAN | `8080` (webapp), `8000` (overseer REST), `5432` (postgres), `9092` (kafka), `50051` (gateway gRPC) free on Ultradian's loopback | `sudo ss -tlnp \| grep -E ':(8080\|8000\|50051\|5432\|9092)'` |

If any row diverges, fix it before continuing or adapt the commands accordingly. The ports list matters: nothing else can be bound to them on Ultradian or the docker bring-up will silently fail one container at a time.

## B.1 · Connect + sync source

From your laptop:

```bash
ssh <user>@ultradian             # adjust hostname / IP
cd ~/git/iteralabs

# Pull the latest from each repo. Atelier-notes is NOT in this monorepo
# (it's an Obsidian vault); only the five public code repos plus the
# internal atelier-overledger payments crate.
for r in atelier-proto atelier-sdk atelier-backend atelier-webapp atelier-infra atelier-overledger; do
    if [[ -d $r ]]; then
        echo "▸ updating $r"
        (cd $r && git pull --ff-only)
    else
        echo "▸ skipping $r (not present)"
    fi
done
```

`atelier-overledger` is an **internal IteraLabs repo** (M3 payments work — Stripe + MoonPay ledger surface). It's not part of the public v0.1 ship; end users never see it. But `atelier-backend/Cargo.toml` path-deps into it, so the overseer build will fail at workspace-manifest load if it's absent on the deploy host. See `product-notes.md §"Platform composition"` for the internal-vs-public framing, and Path A §A.3 for workspace-trap context.

## B.2 · System dependencies (idempotent)

```bash
# Docker
if ! command -v docker >/dev/null; then
    curl -fsSL https://get.docker.com | sh
    sudo usermod -aG docker $USER
    echo "▸ log out and back in (or run 'newgrp docker') so the group change takes effect"
    exit 0   # script-style: stop here, ssh back in
fi

# Common tools
sudo apt-get update
sudo apt-get install -y --no-install-recommends \
    git curl jq openssl postgresql postgresql-client ufw

# Sanity
docker --version
docker compose version    # `compose` not `compose-plugin`
jq --version
```

If `docker compose` is v1 (`docker-compose ...` with a hyphen), upgrade — the manual assumes v2.

## B.3 · Backend stack (production tunables)

```bash
cd ~/git/iteralabs/atelier-infra

# Generate one secret used by both gateway (signs JWTs) and overseer
# (validates them). Both env vars must hold the SAME value.
SECRET=$(openssl rand -base64 48)
cat > .env <<EOF
GATEWAY_JWT_SECRET=$SECRET
JWT_SECRET=$SECRET
AUTH_DEV_BYPASS=true
BINDING_PENDING_GRACE_MS=60000
RUST_LOG=atelier_overseer=info,atelier_gateway=info,info
EOF
chmod 0600 .env             # contains the JWT signing key

# --- Build the three backend images. 
# First: run is ~5–8 min (cold Rust deps);
# Next: runs cache layer-by-layer.
docker compose -f docker-compose.beta.yml build gateway overseer

# --- Bring up infra first
# wait for kafka topics to be created.
docker compose -f docker-compose.beta.yml up -d postgres zookeeper kafka
docker compose -f docker-compose.beta.yml up postgres-init kafka-init

# --- Then the application containers

# --- Local
# The compose `webapp` service is NOT what we ship publicly — 
# it's a dev-mode nginx pointing at localhost:3000.

# --- Live
# Production uses the standalone webapp image built in B.4 below.
docker compose -f docker-compose.beta.yml up -d gateway overseer

# Sanity
docker compose -f docker-compose.beta.yml ps
curl -sf http://localhost:8000/health && echo "▸ overseer healthy"
docker compose -f docker-compose.beta.yml exec kafka \
    kafka-topics --bootstrap-server kafka:29092 --list   # 7 topics expected
```

The 7 expected topics: 

- `lifecycle.events`
- `control.manifests`
- `control.commands`
- `telemetry.reports`
- `artifact.frames`
- `dataset.events`
- `events.bus`.

> **Auth note for the demo.** `AUTH_DEV_BYPASS=true` makes the deploy URL 
self-serve — anyone landing on `/atelier/` can spin up Services. 
For an invite-only alpha, layer Cloudflare Access policies (zero-trust) on 
`/atelier/*` in the Cloudflare dashboard until Iteration 5 ships real auth. 
Cloudflare Access is a separate Cloudflare product 
(Zero Trust → Access → Applications); free tier covers up to 50 users.

> **Firewall.** Ultradian's `localhost:8000` (overseer REST) and 
`localhost:50051` (gateway gRPC) should NOT be reachable from the LAN 
unless you intend remote agents to use them directly. Lock down 
with `sudo ufw deny 8000 && sudo ufw deny 5432 && sudo ufw deny 9092 && sudo ufw enable`. 
Only the webapp container reads `:8000` via `host.docker.internal`, 
and only `cloudflared` reads `:8080`. Gateway exposure for remote agents is handled in B.6.

## B.4 · Build + run the webapp+webdocs image

`atelier-webapp/Dockerfile` is a 3-stage build: 

1. Trunk → SPA
2. MkDocs → static site
3. nginx → serves both. 

all in One image, one container.

```bash
cd ~/git/iteralabs/atelier-webapp

# The provided deploy script does: docker build → stop existing →
# docker run with --restart unless-stopped on port 8080.
./deploy/deploy-lan.sh 8080
```

The script ends with a printout of local + LAN URLs. Confirm locally:

```bash
curl -sI http://localhost:8080/atelier/         # → 200 (SPA index.html)
curl -sI http://localhost:8080/atelier/docs/    # → 200 (MkDocs index.html)
curl -sf http://localhost:8080/api/health       # → JSON health response (proxied to overseer)
```

If `/atelier/docs/` returns 404, the MkDocs build stage failed (likely `--strict` mode caught a broken link). Re-run `docker build -t atelier-webapp .` directly and read the `docs-builder` stage output. The site-source lives in `atelier-webapp/webdocs/docs/`; broken links there fail the entire image build.

## B.5 · Cloudflare Tunnel — install, auth, route

Cloudflare Tunnel runs an outbound process on Ultradian (`cloudflared`) that holds a long-poll connection to Cloudflare's edge. Inbound traffic to `iteralabs.xyz/atelier/*` rides that connection back to `localhost:8080`. No port forwarding on Ultradian, no public IP needed.

### B.5.a · Install cloudflared

```bash
# Cloudflare's apt repo (preferred — auto-updates with `apt upgrade`)
curl -L https://pkg.cloudflare.com/cloudflare-main.gpg \
    | sudo tee /usr/share/keyrings/cloudflare-main.gpg >/dev/null
echo 'deb [signed-by=/usr/share/keyrings/cloudflare-main.gpg] https://pkg.cloudflare.com/cloudflared $(lsb_release -cs) main' \
    | sudo tee /etc/apt/sources.list.d/cloudflared.list
sudo apt-get update
sudo apt-get install -y cloudflared
cloudflared --version
```

(If the apt repo is flaky, fallback: download the `.deb` directly from `https://github.com/cloudflare/cloudflared/releases/latest` — pick `cloudflared-linux-amd64.deb`.)

### B.5.b · Authorize against the iteralabs.xyz zone

```bash
cloudflared tunnel login
```

Opens a Cloudflare auth URL in the terminal. Open it on your laptop, sign in, select the `iteralabs.xyz` zone, authorize. A `cert.pem` lands at `~/.cloudflared/cert.pem` on Ultradian.

### B.5.c · Create the tunnel

```bash
cloudflared tunnel create atelier-demo
# Output ends with: Created tunnel atelier-demo with id <UUID>
```

The UUID and a `<UUID>.json` credentials file go to `~/.cloudflared/`. Note the UUID for the next step.

### B.5.d · Configure ingress

```bash
TUNNEL_UUID=$(cloudflared tunnel list | awk '/atelier-demo/ {print $1}')
echo "tunnel UUID: $TUNNEL_UUID"

cat > ~/.cloudflared/config.yml <<YAML
tunnel: $TUNNEL_UUID
credentials-file: /home/$(whoami)/.cloudflared/${TUNNEL_UUID}.json

ingress:
  # ── Webapp + webdocs (path-based) ───────────────────────────────
  - hostname: www.iteralabs.xyz
    path: /atelier.*
    service: http://localhost:8080
  - hostname: iteralabs.xyz
    path: /atelier.*
    service: http://localhost:8080

  # ── Catch-all: everything else returns 404 ──────────────────────
  - service: http_status:404
YAML
```

The `path: /atelier.*` regex matches both `/atelier/` (SPA root) and `/atelier/docs/` (MkDocs); the nginx config inside the webapp container handles the further split. The catch-all rule is required by `cloudflared` — without it, the config fails validation.

### B.5.e · Route the DNS

This creates CNAME records under `iteralabs.xyz` pointing at the tunnel:

```bash
cloudflared tunnel route dns atelier-demo www.iteralabs.xyz
cloudflared tunnel route dns atelier-demo iteralabs.xyz   # apex; may fail if a flattening CNAME already exists
```

If the apex route fails with "Record already exists", that's fine — the `www` CNAME plus Cloudflare's CNAME-flattening at the zone apex will already cover both. Verify in the Cloudflare DNS dashboard that `www.iteralabs.xyz` points at `<UUID>.cfargotunnel.com`.

### B.5.f · Run as a systemd service

```bash
sudo cloudflared service install
sudo systemctl status cloudflared
sudo journalctl -u cloudflared -f         # follow the logs
```

The service auto-starts on Ultradian reboots and reconnects on transient drops.

### B.5.g · Verify externally (from your laptop)

```bash
# DNS resolves to a Cloudflare IP
dig +short www.iteralabs.xyz             # 104.x.x.x or 172.x.x.x

# HTTPS reaches the dashboard + docs
curl -sI https://www.iteralabs.xyz/atelier/        # → 200
curl -sI https://www.iteralabs.xyz/atelier/docs/   # → 200

# Open in a browser
open https://www.iteralabs.xyz/atelier/            # macOS — `xdg-open` on Linux
```

DNS propagation through Cloudflare is typically 30s. If it still 404s after 2 min, check `journalctl -u cloudflared` for ingress validation errors.

## B.6 · Gateway exposure for end-user agents

End-user agents (Path C) connect to `localhost:50051` on Ultradian for the gRPC TelemetryChannel + CommandChannel + EventSubscribe. Two options for external access; pick based on demo-vs-production posture:

### Option 1 — Demo-grade: open the port via UFW (simpler, no TLS)

```bash
sudo ufw allow 50051/tcp
sudo ufw status
```

End-users set `ATELIER_GATEWAY_URL=http://<ultradian-public-ip-or-LAN-IP>:50051` in their Path C `docker run`. Cleartext gRPC over the open internet — fine for an alive demo on a controlled audience, NOT acceptable for production. Iteration 5 introduces real TLS-on-the-wire for the gateway.

### Option 2 — Tunnel the gRPC port through Cloudflare (TLS-terminated)

Add this to `~/.cloudflared/config.yml`'s `ingress:` list (before the catch-all):

```yaml
  - hostname: gateway.iteralabs.xyz
    service: tcp://localhost:50051
```

Route the DNS:

```bash
cloudflared tunnel route dns atelier-demo gateway.iteralabs.xyz
sudo systemctl restart cloudflared
```

End-users then must run `cloudflared` themselves and connect via `cloudflared access tcp --hostname gateway.iteralabs.xyz --url localhost:50051`, then point the agent at `http://localhost:50051`. Heavier setup on the end-user side; gives proper HTTP/2 framing for gRPC.

For the **alive demo**, Option 1 is the right call — fewer moving pieces on the researcher's machine. Document the public IP / LAN IP in the SpawnModal credential block (the webapp's `gateway_url` field gets set from the overseer's `GATEWAY_URL` env var, so adjust that env var if needed):

```bash
# In atelier-infra/.env, before bringing the stack up:
GATEWAY_URL=http://<ultradian-public-or-LAN-IP>:50051
```

(The default is `http://gateway:50051` which only resolves inside the compose network — useless to external agents.)

